    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3792235036" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3792235036" />
    <a title="carlageek" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17679151-carlageek"><img alt="carlageek" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606840795p2/17679151.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3792235036?book_show_action=true">Jan 31, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="carlageek" class="user" itemprop="url" name="carlageek" href="/user/show/17679151-carlageek">carlageek</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3792235036" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9672867963079854350">It&apos;s always risky to revisit childhood favorites. <br/><br/>When I was in junior high school, the world of this book captivated me. I read it over and over again, vividly imagining the society. I was fascinated by the order of it, and fascinated by the protagonist&apos;s drive to subvert that order.<br/><br/>I picked up the book again after more than 30 years, because I was reminded of it during my recent reading of Yevgeny Zamyatin&apos;s <i>
  <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9774875.We_' title='We  by Yevgeny Zamyatin' rel='nofollow noopener'>We</a>
</i>, a book that is often cited as an inspiration to George Orwell&apos;s <i>1984</i> but was c</span>
  <span id="freeText9672867963079854350" style="display:none">It's always risky to revisit childhood favorites. <br /><br />When I was in junior high school, the world of this book captivated me. I read it over and over again, vividly imagining the society. I was fascinated by the order of it, and fascinated by the protagonist's drive to subvert that order.<br /><br />I picked up the book again after more than 30 years, because I was reminded of it during my recent reading of Yevgeny Zamyatin's <i>
  <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9774875.We_" title="We  by Yevgeny Zamyatin" rel="nofollow noopener">We</a>
</i>, a book that is often cited as an inspiration to George Orwell's <i>1984</i> but was clearly also a significant input to <i>This Perfect Day</i>. And for about the first half of the book, it was everything I remembered. The sharply drawn universe was just as interesting: a global society entirely controlled by computers, where people are identified by "namebers" -- the protagonist's nameber is Li RM35M4419, though his subversive grandfather teaches him to think of himself as Chip -- and wear identifying bracelets that they touch against scanners to obtain the computer's approval to go places and obtain goods. The computer, "Uni" (for UniComp), decides what jobs each person will be trained for, and where they will be sent to perform those jobs. Individuality is suppressed, and conformity is enforced by, in addition to oppressive social conditioning, monthly medical treatments that keep the population docile and submissive. <br /><br />This is, of course, anti-Communist propaganda at its finest. It's also an engrossing world, and an engaging story develops as Chip begins to chafe against the constraints of this society, and faces setbacks as the machinery of conformance identifies his subversive tendencies and acts to further suppress them in a cycle that raises the stakes with each iteration. As a teen, Chip idly asks a girlfriend what job she would choose for herself if she were permitted to do so; alarmed by such an outrageous idea, the girl alerts the authorities and Chip is told he is "sick" and given a stronger treatment. As a young man, he uses his own bracelet to claim extra sketch pads for an friend who has been denied them by Uni, which evidently wants to discourage the friend's artistic tendencies; this time, Chip's own social conditioning overwhelms him with guilt, and he turns himself and his friend in, relieved at the prospect of additional treatments to once again cure him. <br /><br />Later, Chip meets an underground community of subversives; they teach him tricks to get his treatments reduced, and as his mind and body come alive under the lower doses of tranquilizers and hormones, he longs for even more than this group has settled for. Eventually, after another round of being forced back into conformity, Chip formulates a plan to escape the oppressive society. And here, where great (American-style) individuality triumphs over the oppressive sameness of (Soviet-style) control, is where the book bumps off the rails for grown-up me. As part of his escape, Chip kidnaps a woman he knew in the underground community, one who had been caught and treated back into conformance with the society's norms. In service of liberating her from Uni's clutches, he beats her, ties her up every night so she can't escape and turn him in, and ultimately rapes her, all the while claiming that it's for her own good, because he loves her. It's nearly impossible for me to root for Chip after that. <br /><br />There's a very deep problem with the narrative here. It's not just that Chip acts like men have been socialized to act for centuries, or that the woman, Lilac, ultimately submits to it; the implication is that this behavior is innate to men and submission to it is innate to women. Because Lilac and Chip certainly haven't been taught these roles by the society they grew up in; rather, they take them on instinctively once freed of the chemically-induced mildness and respect that has been the norm for their entire lives. This is a pretty sickening view of the human condition, but it's also rather weak storytelling. Why shouldn't freeing Lilac from the prison of Uni make her want to stand up for herself as stridently as it did for Chip? Why didn't Lilac, with as strong a subversive streak as Chip's, find the wherewithal to demand that Chip respect her boundaries and her humanity? Instead, it made her submit to him, and worse, fall in love with him. And that cheapens this imaginative story into yet another midcentury male fantasy. I just don't have time for that kind of bullshit. <br /><br />The rest of the book is interesting, though Chip's behavior toward Lilac is still a little gross, even as he carries through his heroic plan. The revelations toward the ending, and the ending itself, might not make all that much sense in the grand scheme of things, but they are satisfying enough. I'm not going to give the book a star rating because I really did love it wholly as a young person, and it's impossible to rate it now, having read it twice as two entirely different people. There is a lot to admire in here, but it no longer has the shine that it did in my memory. Alas. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9672867963079854350" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

